content.text: JavaScript Use Strict
"use strict"; Defines that JavaScript code should be executed in "strict mode".
content.html: "use strict"; Defines that JavaScript code should be executed in "strict mode".

content.text: The "use strict" Directive
The "use strict" directive was new in ECMAScript version 5.
content.html: The "use strict" directive was new in ECMAScript version 5.

content.text: It is not a statement, but a literal expression, ignored by earlier versions of JavaScript.
content.html: It is not a statement, but a literal expression, ignored by earlier versions of JavaScript.

content.text: The purpose of "use strict" is to indicate that the code should be executed in "strict mode".
content.html: The purpose of "use strict" is to indicate that the code should be executed in "strict mode".

content.text: With strict mode, you can not, for example, use undeclared variables.
content.html: With strict mode, you can not, for example, use undeclared variables.

content.text: All modern browsers support "use strict" except Internet Explorer 9 and lower:
content.html: All modern browsers support "use strict" except Internet Explorer 9 and lower:

content.code_html:
Directive
"use strict" 13.0 10.0 4.0 6.0 12.1

content.text: The numbers in the table specify the first browser version that fully supports the directive.
content.html: The numbers in the table specify the first browser version that fully supports the directive.

content.text: You can use strict mode in all your programs. It helps you to write cleaner code, like preventing you from using undeclared variables.
content.html: You can use strict mode in all your programs. It helps you to write cleaner code, like preventing you from using undeclared variables.

content.text: "use strict" is just a string, so IE 9 will not throw an error even if it does not understand it.
content.html: "use strict" is just a string, so IE 9 will not throw an error even if it does not understand it.

content.text: Declaring Strict Mode
Strict mode is declared by adding "use strict"; to the beginning of a script or a function.
content.html: Strict mode is declared by adding "use strict"; to the beginning of a script or a function.

content.text: Declared at the beginning of a script, it has global scope (all code in the script will execute in strict mode):
content.html: Declared at the beginning of a script, it has global scope (all code in the script will execute in strict mode):

"use strict";x = 3.14;       // This will cause an error 
 because x is not declared

content.text: The "use strict"; Syntax
The syntax, for declaring strict mode, was designed to be compatible with older versions of JavaScript.
content.html: The syntax, for declaring strict mode, was designed to be compatible with older versions of JavaScript.

content.text: Compiling a numeric literal (4 + 5;) or a string literal ("John Doe";) in a JavaScript program has no side effects. It simply compiles to a non existing variable and dies.
content.html: Compiling a numeric literal (4 + 5;) or a string literal ("John Doe";) in a JavaScript program has no side effects. It simply compiles to a non existing variable and dies.

content.text: So "use strict"; only matters to new compilers that "understand" the meaning of it.
content.html: So "use strict"; only matters to new compilers that "understand" the meaning of it.

content.text: Why Strict Mode?
Strict mode makes it easier to write "secure" JavaScript.
content.html: Strict mode makes it easier to write "secure" JavaScript.

content.text: Strict mode changes previously accepted "bad syntax" into real errors.
content.html: Strict mode changes previously accepted "bad syntax" into real errors.

content.text: As an example, in normal JavaScript, mistyping a variable name creates a new global variable. In strict mode, this will throw an error, making it impossible to accidentally create a global variable.
content.html: As an example, in normal JavaScript, mistyping a variable name creates a new global variable. In strict mode, this will throw an error, making it impossible to accidentally create a global variable.

content.text: In normal JavaScript, a developer will not receive any error feedback assigning values to non-writable properties.
content.html: In normal JavaScript, a developer will not receive any error feedback assigning values to non-writable properties.

content.text: In strict mode, any assignment to a non-writable property, a getter-only property, a non-existing property, a non-existing variable, or a non-existing object, will throw an error.
content.html: In strict mode, any assignment to a non-writable property, a getter-only property, a non-existing property, a non-existing variable, or a non-existing object, will throw an error.

content.text: Not Allowed in Strict Mode
Using a variable, without declaring it, is not allowed:

content.text: For security reasons, eval() is not allowed to create variables in the scope from which it was called.
content.html: For security reasons, eval() is not allowed to create variables in the scope from which it was called.

content.code_html:
"use strict";
eval ("x = 2");
alert (x);      // This will cause an error

"use strict";
eval ("var x = 2");
alert (x);    // This will cause an error

eval ("let x = 2");
alert (x);        // This will cause an error

content.text: The this keyword in functions behaves differently in strict mode.
content.html: The this keyword in functions behaves differently in strict mode.

content.text: The this keyword refers to the object that called the function.
content.html: The this keyword refers to the object that called the function.

content.text: If the object is not specified, functions in strict mode will return undefined and functions in normal mode will return the global object (window):
content.html: If the object is not specified, functions in strict mode will return undefined and functions in normal mode will return the global object (window):

content.code:
"use strict";function myFunction() {
alert(this); // will alert "undefined"}myFunction();
content.code_html:
"use strict";
function myFunction() {
  alert(this); // will alert "undefined"
}
myFunction();

content.text: Future Proof!
Keywords reserved for future JavaScript versions can NOT be used as variable names in strict mode.
content.html: Keywords reserved for future JavaScript versions can NOT be used as variable names in strict mode.

content.text: Watch Out!
The "use strict" directive is only recognized at the beginning of a script or a function.
